  <preface xml:id="&projid;.devel.overview">
    <title>Overview</title>
    <para>
      The &gproj; is a <emphasis>meta-project</emphasis> composed
      of a set of <glossterm>knowledge management</glossterm>
      <glossterm>projects</glossterm> and related <glossterm>work
      areas</glossterm>. The primary focus of the &gproj; is to develop
      a set of <glossterm>components</glossterm> and
      <glossterm>toolchains</glossterm> for <glossterm>tasks</glossterm>
      in <glossterm>knowledge management</glossterm>, in support of
      <glossterm>knowledge resource</glossterm> utilization and
      <glossterm>knowledge resource</glossterm> development,
      as centered around social concerns including:
    </para>

    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Natural resource conservation.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Outdoor recreational activity, with regards to resources of
          national and continental geological and ecological heritage
          in the US and broader North America.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Democratic access to <glossterm>information</glossterm>
          as published for the information of the collective audience
          of "We," the <glossterm>citizen</glossterm>
          <glossterm>stakeholders</glossterm>, published actively and
          in normative means by US <glossterm>federal</glossterm>,
          <glossterm>state</glossterm>, <glossterm>county</glossterm>,
          and <glossterm>municipal</glossterm>
          <glossterm>government</glossterm> agencies. This concern
          entails a development of resources in a spirit of
          <emphasis>public informedness</emphasis>, with a politically
          <glossterm>nonpartisan</glossterm> focus, as
          with regards to enabling of pragmatic, democratic access
          to <glossterm>public</glossterm>
          <glossterm>information</glossterm> published by agencies of
          <glossterm>government</glossterm>. This concept is inspired
          originally of Chile's own <orgname>Poderopedia</orgname>,
          but is affected towards emphasis not of concepts and myths
          of "Commercial empire" and "Commerical power", but rather,
          towards concepts of plain, practical, moreover
          <glossterm>legal</glossterm> public information access, in a
          democratic society.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          History of the <glossterm>arts</glossterm>, centering around
          modes of the <glossterm>modern arts</glossterm>, beginning
          with the <glossterm>art movement</glossterm>,
          <glossterm>Dadaism</glossterm>, and relatedly,
          <glossterm>surrealism</glossterm> &mdash; towards the
          origins of <glossterm>modern art</glossterm> as an
          <glossterm>expressive mode</glossterm>
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <glossterm>Sports</glossterm> and physically active modes of
          <glossterm>recreation</glossterm>, as in regards to
          traditional modes  of <glossterm>sports</glossterm>
          <glossterm>reified</glossterm> of the
          <orgname>International Olympic Committee</orgname> and in
          regards to unconventional <glossterm>sports</glossterm>,
          typicaly referred to as "Extreme Sports", in modes
          represented and organized in public endeavors sponsored by
          commercial agencies including <orgname>Red Bull
          GmbH</orgname> and the <orgname>Monster
          beverage company</orgname>.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          The emerging <glossterm>NewSpace</glossterm> industry and
          the heritage of science and goodwill as codified in modes of
          traditional, institutional programs in development of
          <glossterm>civil</glossterm>  <glossterm>aerospace</glossterm>
          <glossterm>systems</glossterm>  and in
          <glossterm>space exploration</glossterm>.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <glossterm>International</glossterm>
          <glossterm>humanitarian</glossterm>
          <glossterm>programs</glossterm>, such as managed by
          the <orgname>UN</orgname> and the <orgname>ICRC</orgname>.
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <para>
      The &gproj; <glossterm>shall</glossterm> serve as a
      <glossterm>content repository</glossterm> and <glossterm>content
      presentation portal</glossterm> for
      <glossterm>public</glossterm> <glossterm>web content</glossterm>
      developed around those <glossterm>topics</glossterm>, so far as
      the content may extend on any single, discrete
      <glossterm>knowledge model</glossterm>
      developed within the &gproj;.
    </para>

  </preface>

